DEPRESSOMETER METHOD
Method
The data of the "Depressometer" project were collected between October 2018 to
February 2021 from 58 patients diagnosed with MDD and 13 therapists during a 16-
session supportive-expressive psychodynamic psychotherapy for depression. The
present document provides a detailed description of the project’s methodology,
including participants, treatment, measures, assessment procedures, and available data
sources.
The main goal of the project was to investigate the interpersonal and intrapersonal
mechanisms underlying change in psychotherapy for Major Depressive Disorder
(MDD), using multimodal, intensive longitudinal psychotherapy dataset. The project
was designed to examine how clients’ and therapists’ emotional, cognitive, behavioral,
physiological, and relational processes unfold within and across sessions, and how
these processes are associated with proximal and distal therapeutic change. The project
includes repeated assessments from both clients and therapists across multiple temporal
resolutions ranging from treatment-level, session-level and follow-up self-reports and
clinician assessments, to fine-grained, within-session linguistic, vocal, facial,
movement, physiological, and hormonal measures collected during sessions. In
addition, a subsample of sessions was manually coded for patients’ changing affective,
behavioral and cognitive experiences, for therapists’ interventions as well as clinicians’
summaries of the sessions. These human annotations were designed to support LLM-
based large-scale further analyses of the full dataset, with the goal of examining
patterns, dynamics and sequences that may facilitate (or hinder) treatment processes
and outcomes. The project was conducted in the Psychotherapy Research Lab at the
Department of Psychology, Bar-Ilan University, Israel. The research was approved by
the Institutional Review Board.
