DEPRESSOMETER METHOD
Participants
Clients: The sample comprised 64 clients diagnosed with Major Depressive Disorder
(MDD). Inclusion criteria were: (a) a primary diagnosis of MDD as indicated by the
Mini-International Neuropsychiatric Interview version 5.0 (MINI; Sheehan et al.,
1998); (b) either a score of 14 or more on the 17-item clinician-administered semi-
structured interview version of the Hamilton Rating Scale for Depression (HRSD;
Hamilton, 1960; Williams, 1988), or a score of 17 or more on the Beck Depression
Inventory-II (BDI-II; Beck, Steer & Brown, 1996). Clients were over 18 years old and
excluded if they presented active suicidality, psychosis, addictions, bipolar disorder,
brain damage, or were currently pregnant and/or have heart problems. Totally, 64
Subjects were assigned to a therapist, and the dyad began a 16-session course of
treatment. Throughout the project, six clients withdrew from therapy before the 12th
session and were considered dropouts and/or declined research use and were removed
from sample, leaving a final cohort of 58 patients diagnosed with MDD (M=36.66
years, SD=9.45, age range 21-61 years).
Of the 58 patients, 53 (91.4%) scored 14 or higher on the HRSD at the intake, 45
(77.6%) scored 17 or higher on the BDI-II at the intake, while all patients met at least
one of these criteria. The majority were female (37 women and 21 men), 31 were
married or in a committed relationship, 23 were single, and 4 divorced. Forty-one had
at least a bachelor's degree, and 49 were either fully or partially employed. The majority
were Israeli-born (42 patients); 12 in the Soviet Union, 1 in France, and 3 did not report
their country of origin. Forty-four were native Hebrew speakers, 8 native Russian
speakers, and 1 failed to complete this item. Also, given their clinical condition, 3
clients chose to take psychiatric medication at some point throughout the treatment.
