Treatment and therapists: Thirteen therapists (7 women and 6 men), whose average
age was 32.2 years (range: 28-41; SD = 3.00), participated in this study and were
advanced trainees in a university clinic with 3 to 7 years of experience. Eight therapists
treated 1 to 4 patients each, and five therapists treated 6-9 patients each (Mean caseload
= 4.46, SD = 2.26). The patients underwent brief (16-session) supportive-expressive
(SE) psychodynamic psychotherapy (Luborsky & Mark, 1991; Luborsky, 1984)
adapted to the treatment of depression (Luborsky et al., 1995), using supportive
techniques such as affirmation and empathic validation, alongside expressive
techniques such as interpretation and confrontation. SE therapy has been reported
effective in the treatment of depression (Gibbons et al., 2012; 2016). The therapists
were trained and supervised by senior clinicians with extensive SE expertise and
received weekly individual and group supervision.
Procedure
Clients were recruited through advertisements published on social network
platforms, offering short-term psychodynamic therapy for depression-related
symptoms. Overall, 531 inquiries were made. A clinical assessment team consisting of
MA level clinical trainees, who received group supervision from senior clinicians,
assessed applicants for the study. 364 applicants went through brief telephone screening
and completed the Beck Depression Inventory-II (BDI-II; Beck, Steer & Brown, 1996),
as a preliminary filtering criterion. 128 subjects were invited to an intake interview, as
there BDI-II score was 17 or above ("borderline clinical depression" or severe than that)
and they did not presented any of the excluded criteria. During this intake meeting, the
MINI and HAM-D clinical interviews were administered. Applicants who met the
inclusion and exclusion criteria were invited to a second meeting, where they were
requested to sign an informed consent form and were familiarized with the therapy.
