showed reliable BDI improvement (reliable change index [RCI] = 5.78). For the ORS,
among the 46 patients who began treatment below the ORS clinical cutoff (24), 19
(41.3%) crossed above the ORS clinical cutoff by the end of treatment, and 25 (54.3%)
showed reliable ORS improvement (RCI = 5). For the HSCL, among the 43 patients
who began above the HSCL clinical cutoff (1.92), 21 (48.8%) ended treatment below
the cutoff, but only 9 (20.9%) showed reliable HSCL improvement (RCI = 0.79).
Across the broader sample, 52.7% ended treatment below the HRSD clinical cutoff.
For the BDI, 62.5% ended treatment below the BDI clinical cutoff, and 67.9% showed
reliable BDI improvement (RCI). For the ORS, 28 (48.3%) ended treatment above the
cutoff, and 44.8% showed reliable ORS improvement (RCI). For the HSCL, 60.3%
ended treatment below the HSCL cutoff, but only 15.5% showed reliable HSCL
improvement (RCI).
Transcriptions
All available videotaped sessions (total of 816 sessions) were transcribed by research
assistants. The transcription protocol followed general guidelines (Mergenthaler &
Stinson, 1992). Transcribers completed a one-day training workshop and attended
monthly supervision meetings throughout the transcription process. Training included
guidelines for handling confidential information, replacing names with pseudonyms,
and masking identifying details. The Hebrew transcripts were translated to English
using Google Cloud's Translation API service, driven by the superior performance of
LLMs in English, which currently represents a cutting edge in NLP capabilities. An
average of 14.07 sessions were transcribed per patient (SD = 3.00), yielding a total of
816 sessions. The corpus included approximately six million words. On average,
sessions included 7,758 words (SD = 1,756), of which 5,310 were patient utterances
