Measures
Pre, post and follow-up treatment semi-structured interview and self-report
questionnaires:
The Hamilton Rating Scale for Depression (HRS-D; Hamilton, 1960; Williams,
1988) is a clinician-administered semi-structured interview that can provide an
indication of depression and act as a guide for evaluating recovery. It is designed to
assess depression severity by probing mood, guilt, suicidal ideation, insomnia, agitation
or retardation, anxiety, weight loss, and somatic symptoms. Clients are rated on 17
dimensions with a 3- or 5-point scale. In this study, a summed score of 14 or above was
used as the cutoff score for MDD.
Beck Depression Inventory-II (BDI-II; Beck et al., 1996) is a 21-item self-report
measure of depression that asks respondents to rate the severity of their symptoms
during the previous week using a Likert scale (19 items use a 4-point scale, 2 items use
a 7-point scale). The BDI-II consists of two underlying factors assessing cognitive‐
affective and somatic symptoms of depression (Whisman, Perez, & Ramel, 2000).
Individual item scores are summed to create a total severity score ranging from 0 to 63.
Depressive severity is categorized using the following ranges: 0 to 10 (minimal), 11 to
16 (mild), 17-20 (borderline), 21 to 30 (moderate), 31-40 (severe), ≥40 (extreme). High
internal consistency (.93) and significant (p ≤ .01) inter-correlations were found
between the BDI-II total scale and the Behavior and Symptom Identification Scale 24-
item Depression/Functioning (r .79) and Overall (r .82) subscales (Subica et al., 2014).
Outcome Questionnaire 45 (OQ-45; Lambert et al. 1996) is a 45-item self-report
measure that captures functioning in three domains, all of which have shown good
