Working Alliance Inventory (WAI-SR; Hatcher & Gillaspy, 2006) is a 12-item short
form of the Working Alliance Inventory (WAI; Horvath & Greenberg, 1989), based on
Bordin’s (1979) tripartite conceptualization of the client–therapist relationship (degree
of agreement on goals, concordance on tasks, and strength of the therapeutic bond).
After each session, clients and therapists used a 7-point Likert scale to rate how
accurately each item describes their current therapy experience. The WAI-SR has good
reliability, with alpha coefficients for overall internal reliability ranging from .85 to .95.
The reliability estimates of the subscales have also demonstrated fairly high alpha
coefficients: .82 to .88 on the Task subscale, .82 to .87 on the Goal subscale, and .85
on the Bond subscale.
Session Evaluation Scale (SES; Hill & Kellems, 2002), which was administered
after each session. The original version contains four items (e.g., “I did not feel satisfied
with what I got out of this session). Clients rate each statement on a 5-point scale
ranging from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree). Hill & Kellems, 2002 reported
that SES yielded adequate internal consistency reliability estimates in two different
samples (α = .89), as well as correlates with post-session measures of skills used in-
session and the therapeutic relationship. As in Lent, et al. (2006) a single item from the
SES was added, asking to “rate the overall effectiveness of this session” from 1 (not
effective) to 5 (highly effective). In our sample, this item correlated with the original
SES items (rs = [.39, .76]). Finally, in our dataset, SES items showed good internal
reliability estimates (Cronbach’s α = .84).
Profile of Mood States (POMS; McNair et al., 1992), which was administered after
each session. POMS is a widely used instrument that assesses mood variables. For the
purpose of this project, we used an abbreviated version of the measure, which was
adapted for intensive repeated measurements (Cranford et al., 2006) and consists of 12
