McCarthy & Barber, 2009). Additionally, we excluded the person-centered scale (3
items), given its high documented overlap with the process-experiential scale (e.g., r =
0.86; e.g., McAleavey & Castonguay, 2014; McCarthy & Barber, 2009).
Coding systems and projects:
All coding systems were applied on the "working phase", from 5 sessions out of 16
(for each therapy). Those were the same sessions which were chosen to be the sessions
that physiological activity and saliva samples were collected in them. "Working phase"
is defined based on Auszra et al. (2013) as the 15 minutes before the last 5 minutes of
the session. This phase is considered to be that part of session in which clients are likely
to be the most engaged in therapeutic work.
Multimodal Interpersonal and Intrapersonal Dynamics (MIND; Atzil-Slonim,
2025).
This coding project drew on the Multimodal Intrapersonal and Interpersonal
Dynamics (MIND; Atzil-Slonim, 2025) framework, a shared transtheoretical process
language that integrates insights from diverse psychotherapy theories and empirical
findings to identify the intrapersonal and interpersonal dynamics linked to therapeutic
change. The MIND framework reflects two major shifts in clinical science: from trait-
like conceptions of psychopathology toward modifiable self-states and intrapersonal
dynamics, and from manualized treatments toward personalized interpersonal
dynamics that flexibly respond to patients' evolving verbal and nonverbal cues. This
framework provides its empirical implementation by breaking down patients'
experiences into well-accepted core experiential building blocks (Affect, Behavior,
Cognition, Desire [ABCD]; Greenberg, 2012; Mcnair et al., 1992; Revelle, 2007) and
therapist interventions (McCullough, 1988). By attuning to patients' shifting self-states,
therapists can help patients to process and dampen maladaptive ABCD elements while
15

DEPRESSOMETER METHOD
amplifying more adaptive ones and dialogue among them, eventually facilitating
improved well-being (Stiles, 2001). It offers both a common language for representing
how these elements co-occur and interact moment-by-moment in therapy, and a
foundation for translating and teaching AI models the fundamental concepts of complex
psychotherapeutic constructs.
Session selection and transcription. For each patient we aimed to choose a session
from the working phase of therapy, defined in previous research as the mid-treatment
period linked to higher patient emotional productivity and better outcomes (Auszra et
al., 2013). To maintain consistency, we focused on sessions 8 to 11. The videotaped
sessions were transcribed by research assistants. These transcriptions were also
automatically translated to English (using the secure services of Google Translate) in
order to then use the coded transcriptions in AI models.
Annotation was done at different levels of temporal granularity (speech-turn level,
5 min segments, session level), which highlighted evidence in the transcribed text to
justify choices. At the speech-turn level, annotators coded patients’ states with respect
to the presence and adaptiveness level of four core elements: (ABCD; Lazarus &
Rafaeli, 2023). Affect was annotated using both the global valence expressed (i.e.,
Negative, Positive, Neutral, e.g., Greenberg, 2012) and the specific emotion(s)
identified (POMS; Mcnair et al. 1992). The remaining three elements (Behavior,
Cognition, and Desire) were annotated using a modified version of the Core Conflictual
Relationship Theme (CCRT; Luborsky and Crits-Christoph 1997). The annotators
defined a "presence" scale (0-4) and an "adaptivity" scale (-2-2) for each self-state
dimension (Affect, Behavior-Self, Behavior-Other, Cognition-Self, Cognition-Other,
Desire). The MIND scheme integrates components that are considered central across a
wide range of psychological theories. Previous studies have shown moderate to high
16

DEPRESSOMETER METHOD
inter-rater reliability for each scale (e.g., Slonim et al. 2013; Berk 2013; Mayer et al.
2024; Mccullough et al. 2003).
At a predefined 5-minute segment level, clinical judges provided ratings for micro-
level outcome, therapeutic alliance, and therapeutic rupture. Micro-level outcome was
rated using a single item adapted from the general well-being dimension of the Outcome
Rating Scale (ORS), whereas alliance and rupture were rated using single items adapted
from the Session-level Working Alliance Inventory - Observer version (S-WAI-O;
Berk, 2013) and the Post-Session Questionnaire (PSQ), respectively. For each
construct, the item wording and coder instructions were explicitly based on the
theoretical definitions and rating anchors of the original validated measures, tailored
for application at the micro-level. All scales within the MIND scheme have been
applied in previous studies across diverse therapeutic approaches (e.g., Slonim et al.,
2013; Grenyer & Marceau, 2022), supporting their validity in capturing complex
therapeutic processes. The segment-level Alliance/Reciprocity, Tension/Rupture, and
Micro-level Outcome items were scored on 5-point Likert scales that were treated as
approximately interval.
Four annotators, three Master’s students in clinical psychology and one doctoral
student, annotated the selected sessions using the MIND scheme. The annotators
received comprehensive training from a clinical expert and ongoing supervision. The
annotators underwent a preliminary training phase, during which they received iterative
feedback and conducted reconciliation meetings to enhance consistency and interrater
reliability. Annotators read each full session transcript but coded only the working
phase.
Inter-Annotator Agreement (IAA)
17

DEPRESSOMETER METHOD
IAA was evaluated on a 14-session (42 segments; 24% of the data) subsample that
was independently coded by two raters, each pair randomly drawn from the full pool of
four trained annotators. Rater pairings varied across segments, yielding an unbalanced
two-of-four design. Agreement was quantified with Gwet's chance-corrected
coefficients - AC1 for nominal categories, AC2 with quadratic weights for ordinal
ratings, and the Jaccard index for multi-label sets - alongside Krippendorff's α (nominal
or quadratic-weighted, matched to the coefficient type). Both families are defined for
unbalanced multi-rater designs (Gwet, 2014; Krippendorff, 2018); Fleiss' κ, which
assumes a constant number of ratings per unit, is not reported.
Because psychotherapy markers typically exhibit low trait prevalence within a
segment, kappa-family coefficients deflate sharply even when observed agreement is
high - the "kappa paradox" (Feinstein & Cicchetti, 1990; Wongpakaran et al., 2013).
Gwet's AC1/AC2 use an expected-disagreement formulation that is approximately
invariant to prevalence (Gwet, 2014). We treat AC1/AC2 as the primary coefficient and
report α alongside for transparency, following recent annotation-heavy work in clinical
(Svantesson et al., 2024) and computational-linguistic (Yu et al., 2024; Bianco et al.,
2026) settings; divergences between coefficients are interpreted substantively (cf. Vach
& Gerke, 2023). The Jaccard index is used for multi-label annotations to prevent mutual
