LLM interventions versus human therapist interventions.
Using a sample of 300 therapy session contexts, each containing both human-
and LLM-generated responses, served as the evaluation dataset. We developed an
LLM-based framework composed of four specialized LLM agents, each representing a
different therapeutic dimension, and a Judge-LLM that selects the most appropriate
intervention. Expert clinical judges assessed interventions for their typicality and
quality.
Grounded in intervention types widely regarded as central across diverse
psychotherapeutic approaches, such as empathy, meaning-making, exploration, and
directive interventions (e.g., McCullough, 1988; Summers et al., 2024), we developed
a final framework consisted of four expert LLMs, each prompted to focus on a specific
dimension of therapy and counseling: (1) Supportive Agent: fosters empathy,
acceptance, and validation, and recognizes patients’ feelings, growth, and struggles,
thereby strengthening their self-worth and confidence in their capacity to change; (2)
Meaning-making Agent: expands the patient’s awareness and self-understanding by
providing new meaning and interpretation of core conflicts, patterns, and hidden voices;
(3) Exploratory Agent: encourages patients to explore, expand, and uncover deeper
layers of their feelings, thoughts, memories, and experiences by inviting expression of
additional self-voices, wishes, needs, and concerns; (4) Directive Agent: actively
guides the therapy by providing structured instruction, teaching new skills, setting
goals, or suggesting tasks and behavioral change.
The framework operated in two steps. First, for a given dialogue context segment
between the therapist and patient, each agent was prompted to generate an intervention
aligned with its expertise. Second, to maintain coherence and effectiveness, a Judge-
LLM was initialized to evaluate the four responses and select the most appropriate one
20

DEPRESSOMETER METHOD
based on contextual relevance, fluency, and alignment with best therapeutic practices.
Overall, this framework is inherently interpretable since the Judge-LLM provides
reasoning for each decision. To regulate response length and variability, we set the
temperature parameter to be 0.7 and enforced a minimum length of five tokens (words).
This balanced response diversity and coherence while preventing outputs that were
excessively verbose or too brief.
Evaluation of the Interventions. A different team of three expert judges evaluated
the human therapists and LLM intervention outputs. All three judges were clinical
psychologists in training who were blind to the intervention provider (i.e., LLM/
Human) throughout the evaluation period. During the training period, the team held
five meetings, each lasting 1.5 hours. During these meetings, the annotators practiced
applying the annotation scheme guidelines on intervention examples and annotated a
separate training sample of six dialogue contexts while discussing incongruencies.
After this training period, the team began annotating a sample of 300 randomly selected
conversation dialogues. For each dialogue, two interventions were annotated (Human
therapist and LLM-generated) in random order. The entire team annotated sixty
interventions (30 pairs, 10% of the sample) to assess inter-rater reliability. The
remaining 270 pairs were evaluated independently by each judge (~90 pairs per
annotator). Weekly coordination meetings were held to review the dialogue contexts
annotated by the entire team. These contexts were staggered throughout the annotation
process.
Coding Interactive Behavioral Manual (CIB; Feldman, 1998).
The CIB is a well-validated global rating system of dyadic interactions with versions
for coding social interactions in infancy, childhood, adolescence and adulthood. The
CIB has good psychometric properties and has shown sensitivity to differences related
21

DEPRESSOMETER METHOD
to age, interactive partner, cultural background, and risk conditions (Feldman, 2012;
Feldman, Bamberger, & Kanat-Maymon, 2013; Lebowitz et al., 2017). The version of
the CIB adapted to psychotherapy (Feldman, 2016) has 48 scales: 26 are scales for the
therapist, 22 for the client, and 10 scales for the dyad as a whole and addressing dyadic
measures. Each scale produces a single value for the entire segment being coded and is
rated on a Likert scale of 1=low to 5=high. Overall, approximately five pre-selected
sessions were coded for 54 patients (overall = 249 sessions).
In the study of Stolowicz-Melman et al. (2026), following previous studies (Pratt et
al., 2017; Priel, A., Djalovski, A., Zagoory‐Sharon, O., & Feldman, R., 2019;
Schneiderman, I., Kanat-Maymon, Y., Ebstein, R. P., & Feldman, R., 2014), dyadic
synchrony and dyadic tension were used by averaging CIB discrete codes (namely
reciprocity, synchrony and fluency for dyadic synchrony; and constriction and tension
for dyadic tension). Coding was conducted in 143 sessions for 30 patients, by trained
master’s degree clinicians who watched the working phase of the five sampled recorded
sessions. Reliability was conducted in 25 sessions and the ICC for the intra-rater
reliability was 0.76, indicating good to excellent inter-rater reliability (range = 0.57-
0.87; Cicchetti, 1994).
