The CEAS-III is a 7-point, anchored ordinal scale that assesses the quality and
intensity of client emotions on the basis of the evaluation of the client’s degree of
arousal from voice, body language, facial expressions and the degree of restriction of
expression. Embedded within the scale are ratings of both verbal and nonverbal
indicators of both intensity and constriction of emotional expression. In addition, the
characteristics of arousal of different emotions at the same levels can vary depending
on the emotion being expressed. Assessment is divided into two parts: first,
the valence of the main emotion the client experience is identified (positive, negative
soft or hard); second, the overall level of intensity of the client’s emotion (modal
intensity), as well as the peak intensity, or intensity of the maximally aroused moment,
are rated (Warwar & Greenberg, 1999). Upper levels indicate higher arousal intensities
and lower levels indicate restriction of emotional expression.
Previous studies have reported interrater reliability scores ranging from .75 to .81,
and average emotional arousal has been shown to predict outcome (Greenberg et al.,
2007; Missirlian et al., 2005; Warwar, 2003). Raters received approximately 16 hours
of training on the coding systems (adapted from the Client Expressed Emotional
Arousal Scale III-Revised; Warwar & Greenberg, 1999). Following the period of
training, all raters were given the same 4 therapy sessions to rate independently in order
to establish reliability. 10% of the sessions were randomly selected and were coded
simultaneously and independently by two raters, in order to monitor the coding
reliability. The average ICC for emotional arousal intensity was .74. The average
percent of agreement for emotional valance was 90%.
The PIC is designed to examine therapist interventions and the impact of these
interventions in dynamic orientated therapies. Using videotapes of Short-Term
Dynamic psychotherapy sessions, the PIC annotates eight standard therapist
23

DEPRESSOMETER METHOD
interventions. In this study, a modified, broader version of PIC was used, annotating 10
therapist interventions: Clarification (statements that repeat, organize or reflect the
client's words, sometimes in slightly different language, but without interpretation or
conclusion. The therapist can also reflect an emotion or experience of the client in
words, and not just verbal content. Clarifications do not present the client with ideas or
possibilities that are not already in the conscious mind); Support (statements that
express interest, affection, understanding, praise, indication or approval towards the
client and his experience). Statements by the therapist expressing support for the client
in moments of difficulty, as well as an attempt to strengthen the client's sense of value,
confidence or trust in his abilities and skills.; Directive (statements that guide, direct
and advise the client to react in a certain way during or after the session. The therapist
leads actively and directs the client how to think or act. In this intervention, the therapist
can teach the client new skills, encourage behavioral change, challenge thinking
distortions, and give the client different tasks); Information (providing information to
the client in a didactic or educational manner, but does not contain advice); Expansion
(comments/questions the therapist uses to gather information and learn more discourse
about the experiences and the content in question. Any extension or invitation by the
therapist to the client to add information); Self-Disclosure ( therapists deliberately talk
about –themselves in reference to their own feelings or thoughts during the session or
disclosure of information about their personal life such as beliefs, values, life
circumstances and past experiences); Emotion-Focused (therapists direct clients to
focus on their emotional experience, by investigating the experience in question and by
directing attention to the present moment. This can involve using questions and
statements that draw attention to the emotional experience); Filler (speech turns in
which the therapist uses a single word/or noncommittal murmur to confirm and express
24

DEPRESSOMETER METHOD
listening and understanding the client's words); Not Defined (when impossible to
determine the dominant characteristic of the intervention and distinguish it from other
interventions); Interpretation (a response from the therapist that allows a new insight
to emerge in the client. The therapist suggests a new way to explain the unconscious
meaning of the client’s contents and behaviors and links them to relations to self and/or
others that characterize the client and repeat themselves maladaptively. The
interpretation should contribute something beyond what the client states openly.
Interpretation often deals with the exposure and explanation of clients’ relationship
pattern towards themselves or towards others. Confrontational responses are also
included in this category, in which the therapist highlights the conflict from the client's
words and brings this to the surface).
To examine inter-rater reliability an analysis of 22 sessions coded by different
combinations of raters yielded a Cohen's kappa coefficient of .68. Kappa values
between .40 and .75 are considered to represent fair-to-good agreement above chance
(Fleiss et al., 1981).
Relationship Anecdote Paradigm interview (RAP; Luborsky, 1998) and CCRT
Formulations. RAP was developed as a method of gathering interpersonal episodes,
from which the CCRT can be extracted. Subjects are asked to 4 specific interpersonal
interactions, which took place between them and significant people in their lives. The
CCRT model views interpersonal patterns as consisting of three basic components: (i)
an individual’s wishes, needs, or intentions during an interpersonal interaction with a
specific other (W); (ii) the actual or expected responses of the other (RO); and (iii) the
responses of the self (RS). Each episode is then coded on the wishes and responses of
other and self, and the components that appear most frequently in the interview form
the subject's CCRT.
25

DEPRESSOMETER METHOD
In this project, patients were asked to tell narratives about their parents, from
which the parent CCRT were derived. The CCRT method, and the RAP, were tested
in numerous studies, in which inter judge reliability was high (Luborsky, 1998). In
addition, the RAP method was administered in Hebrew as well, achieving similar
reliability and agreement between judges (Atzil-Slonim, Tishby & Shefler, 2015;
Slonim, Shefler & Tishby, 2013; Tishby & Vered, 2011). In the current project, RAP
was administered and coded at two time points during treatment: at the beginning (T1)
and end (T2) of treatment. Of the 51 patients included in the RAP data, 47 patients
(92.2%) had RAP data at both T1 and T2, 2 patients (3.9%) had T1 data only, and 2
patients (3.9%) had T2 data only. Judges were MA-level clinical trainees who were
trained until they reached reliability above .80 on all scales.
Additionally, based on the interpersonal themes identified through the CCRT,
including patients’ wishes (W) and responses of self (RS) and other (RO), therapists
presented each patient with a personalized case formulation midway through treatment,
typically in session 8 or a subsequent session. A total of 56 formulations were
documented and available.
Physiological, hormonal and behavioral measures
During 5 of the 16 sessions (mostly in sessions 2, 5, 8, 11, and 14), physiological
activity, i.e., electrocardiography (ECG) and electro-dermal activity (EDA) were
recorded. Continuous physiological activity measures were recorded from both clients
and their therapists at a sample rate of 1 kHz with an integrated system and software
package (Mindware Technology, Gahanna, OH). ECG and EDA were recorded using
a wireless mobile device connected to each subject with disposable electrodes; overall
5 for each subject, 3 for the ECG (on the right clavicle and the two lower bones of the
thorax) and 2 for EDA (on the distal phalange of the index and middle fingers). Using
26

DEPRESSOMETER METHOD
Mindware software, ECG artifacts were edited out based on visual inspection as well
as on the overall R-R distribution using a validated algorithm. In addition EDA signals
were examined on Mindware software for gross motion artifacts and non-responsive
subjects.
Hormonal system measure:
During 5 of the 16 sessions (mostly in sessions 2, 5, 8, 11, and 14), saliva samples
were collected from both clients and their therapists, immediately prior and
immediately after each sampled session. Before such sessions, subjects were requested
to arrive to therapy at least an hour after eating and to avoid drinking or chewing gum
at least half an hour prior to sample collection. Immediately prior to the sampled
session, subjects filled out a questionnaire regarding their medical and physiological
condition on that day. After collection, the samples were frozen at −20°C. Oxytocin
(OT) analysis was conducted for all samples in Prof. Ruth Feldman's laboratory, located
at the Interdisciplinary Center Herzliya. Concentration of OT (in picograms per
milliliter – pg/ml) in these samples was determined in duplicates. The assay was
performed according to the manufacturer's kit instructions, by using auto-analyzer
EVO75 (Tecan Germany). The OT concentration was calculated using Magellan
software, according to the kits’ calibration curve. Three internal controls in the low,
mid and high range were added for quality control. In case of a deviation exceeding two
standard deviations, the samples from that plate were excluded and samples were rerun.
Behavioral measures
Body Movement signals of both clients and therapists, quantified with motion
energy analysis (MEA; Ramseyer, 2020), measuring differences in pixel values
between consecutive video frames. Following Ramseyer (2020), a 20-pixel threshold
for minimal movement was used that enables easy distinction between movement and
27

DEPRESSOMETER METHOD
no-movement. Values under this threshold, likely caused by minimal light changes or
video noise, were automatically excluded from the analyses.
Also, facial expressions, using FaceReader-9 (Höfling et al., 2020), were analyzed.
The FaceReader-9 was used to extract emotional responses from the video recordings,
allowing for assessment of emotional responses via video imagery analysis (Höfling et
al., 2020) based on the Facial Action Coding System (FACS; Ekman & Friesen, 1976).
The FaceReader provides built-in facial action unit analysis and emotional expression
scoring. Based on the Circumplex Model of Affect (Russell, 1980), valence was
measured on a continuous scale from −1 (most negative emotion) to +1 (most positive
emotion), and was captured at a rate of 25 frames per second. We used the 1-second
mean valence score to evaluate the emotional responses of the participants moment-by-
moment during a session.
